Numerical measurements of vitals are all continuous variables as they can be any number within a specified range and anything in between.

Our categorical variables are not values with a range of multiple outcomes, they are variables assigned 0, 1, or 2 to show which "category" they belong to. For example, you cannot have 1.5 blood vessels, but it is entirely possible to have a maximum heart rate of 142.49

Step 2. There is a roughly equal representation of people prone to heart attacks to those who aren't.

Working with a balanced dataset is important depending on what information we are trying to gather. If we are trying to figure out the percentage of population that is at risk for a heart attack, then "balancing" would make our results biased. If we are trying to find which variables help us predict the likelihood of a heart attack (such as this assignment), then a balanced dataset is very important.

We can choose to "fix" an imbalanced dataset by increasing the minority population or reducing the majority population through many means, including deletion, replacement, and resampling.

We can also change our evaluation metric to one that takes into account this imbalanced population, such as f1 scores.

Step 8. Logistical and KNN are useful in solving the statement

one hot encoding changes multiple categorical variables in a single column into multiple singular columns that accept binary values. label encoding works similarly but for ordinal variables, and keeps the single column format BUT assigns all the possible values into numerical integers as opposed to binary values.

multicolinearity basically shows if two variables are describing the same factor within a dataset, this is bad because this "factor" will have increased importance within our algorithms, and give us inaccurate results as the weighing is much larger than it should be. The easiest way to detect and handle multicolinearity is to use pairplots and to drop.

scaling data is important for numerical based algorithms. if a variable uses very large integers to express values, then our algorithms will weigh these variables much higher within their formula, using a scaler such as a minmax scaler allows us to "standardize" all of our numerical data into a range of 0.00 to 1.00, ensuring that we still convey distance within our data set without having such a skewed weighing for "larger" variables.

heatmaps are non parametric while kde distribution is parametric ( using our target variable as the parameter ) our parametric algorithm can show deeper analysis but it requires us to specify our data to fit certain parameters. our nonparametric algorithm does not demand that our data fit any requirement, and thus is more flexible for different datasets, however, we may miss out on seeing the finer details that a parametric algorithm may make visible to us.

For missing values, the standard way to deal with them is to replace them with a mean/median/mode of the data depending if it is numerical/ordinal/categorical. Another way to deal with values is to delete the row associated with the missing value, however, this is not a popular method as a lot of usable information is lost this way. Lastly, we can consider using different algorithms that are built to handle these kinds of inconsistencies in our data.

If so, which scaling method did you use and why? Is there a specific reason you selected these 2 models? How did the 2 models compare against each other?

I scaled my data because KNN and Logistic Regression algorithms do not work well with unscaled data.

While I originally wanted to scale using a RobustScaler because we have many outliers in our dataset. In this context, outliers are not a bad thing to affect our dataset! Because we are trying to study the relationship between our variables and the target variable, our outliers would help show how well our variables can predict heart attacks when it comes to extreme values. I opted for the MinMax scaler as I did not not want to affect the data in any major way.

K nearest neighbors is a useful model because we have a lot of data to work with, and because this is a classification question in that we classify a patient as heart attack prone or not.

Logistic Regression is useful because this works best with probabilities, and our target variable is trying to predict the risk of a heart attack in an individual.

from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score
from sklearn.model_selection import KFold
#cross validate with kfolds
kf = KFold(n_splits=5, shuffle=True, random_state=42)

#store scores using cross validate
log_reg_scores = cross_val_score(log_reg_model, X, y, cv=kf)
knn_scores = cross_val_score(knn, X, y, cv=kf)

# Print mean scores
print("Mean Accuracy - Logistic Regression:", log_reg_scores.mean())
print("Mean Accuracy - K Nearest Neighbors:", knn_scores.mean())
